label chapter17:

    # [Scene: Tidewatch Lab | Morning — cold, thin light after rain]

    scene bg ch15_3be532_1 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Low, mournful cello; a distant gull, wind through broken glass]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Quiet drip of condensation; the soft click of a refrigerator compressor]
    "You stand over the workbench with the ledger folded flat, the pages heavy with numbers that feel like indictment. Outside, the promenade's sodium lamps still buzz; the town is not yet awake, but the barge's horn from last night seems to have settled into your bones."
    "The choice you made—refusing to sign interim results—is a slow bruise spreading outward. You told the council you'd hold the line until external peers could verify the analysis. You told them science had to be unimpeachable."
    "You told them you would not lend credibility to a model that might steer public funds into a plan that sinks what it claimed to save."
    "The ledger sits between you and the rest of the world, and beyond it a delay forms like a knot in rope."
    show isla_morgan at left:
        zoom 0.7

    isla_morgan "We can't let this go out with caveats. I won't put my name on a half-explanation."
    "Luca Moreno leans against the doorway, tool loops at his hip glinting with wet salt. He runs a hand through his sun-bleached hair with that impulsive motion you have learned to read: not just frustration, but the itch to act. His voice is low, but edged with urgency."
    show luca_moreno at right:
        zoom 0.7

    luca_moreno "Holding it won't make the council read us any kinder. They're desperate, Isla — people are scared. Developers smell that. They'll paint silence as obstruction."
    "You watch his fingers curl around the red bandana tied at his wrist. The fabric is a small, stubborn color in the lab's gray light."

    isla_morgan "I'd rather be accused of caution than complicit in something that collapses when the sea tests it."
    "Luca Moreno exhales sharply."

    luca_moreno "Caution doesn't stop contractors from moving their cranes. They move money fast when the town falters. We need the town with us — not just on paper."
    "There is a beat where both of you listen to the lab breathe: the soft rasp of charts settling, the lab fridge complaining, the muffled click of rain against the window one last time."

    menu:
        "Double-check the sediment cores one more time":
            "You set the cores on the bench, fingers smelling of cold mud. The microscope lens fogs with your breath as you run the samples through one more filter — an old habit, a small assurance."
        "Call the external peer right now and walk them through the ledger":
            "You dial the number with hands that shake a little less than your heartbeat. The call connects; you begin to read aloud, slower than usual, as if each sentence could change the weather."

    # --- merge ---
    "Narrative continues with Luca moving closer and the conversation about action."
    "Luca Moreno moves closer, not touching the ledger but close enough for the heat of someone who still believes coordination can fix a strategic pause."

    luca_moreno "I'll take to the promenade. I'll talk to people, start the workshops—get them seeing the plan so when funding returns they don't forget us. And I'll call every volunteer group in the county."
    "You look at him. He's half-hope, half-bullet; you admire both halves and fear them equally."

    isla_morgan "Don't tie yourself to promises you can't keep. Developers can buy labor and banners; they can't be voted out with the high tide."
    "Luca Moreno gives you a quick, wry smile that doesn't reach his eyes."

    luca_moreno "Then promise me you won't be alone in the lab all week."
    "You swallow. You want to say yes. You want to say that if he fights with his smile and you with your models, that's enough. But the ledger feels heavier than companionship. You tuck it into a waterproof case as if sealing a wound."
    # [Scene: Greyhaven Promenade | Late Morning]
    hide isla_morgan
    hide luca_moreno

    scene bg ch15_3be532_2 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Tense, staccato strings; the murmur of public voices undercut by distant mechanical thumps]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Hammers, a PA system testing; a child's cry cut off by wind]
    "Luca Moreno becomes movement incarnate. You watch him unlock a megaphone, hand it to Ravi for signage, teach a small group how to chant a message that isn't only about anger but about the people who fish here, who paint roofs, who plant rooftop beds."
    "He interrupts a developer's contractor supervisor with a gravelly joke that defuses a heated exchange for a second, and in that second dozens listen. You walk the fringe — answering questions when you can, explaining why"
    "a review matters — and learning the hard limit of words when cranes are visible and promises glint like new metal."
    "Aria Chen's presence at the edge of the promenade is complex and unreadable. She stands with a slim digital badge glinting on her coat, her briefcase closed like a held breath. When your eyes find hers,"
    "she lifts a hand in something nearly like a salute and then looks away. There is no malice stamped across her face; there is measurement, a ledger of her own."
    "You do not know if her calculations include the developer's accelerated mobilization. You only know that capital moves with its own tide."

    menu:
        "Confront Aria about the contractors":
            "You move toward her, voice steady. Aria answers with a practiced calm, her words a currency you cannot refuse. The conversation shapes into policy language fast; you leave with more questions than assurances."
        "Keep focused on the community and let Luca handle political bridges":
            "You turn back to the people clustered around the breakwaters model. A child presses a damp finger to a map; you explain each reed, each reef, feeling the small ache of hands you could not hold fast."

    # --- merge ---
    "The decision sets you and Luca on different fronts—verification and public scaffolding."
    "You choose to let Luca Moreno build the public scaffolding while you press for verification. The decision seems like the only principled one. It also sets your two fronts in opposite directions: evidence waits for peers; activism negotiates immediate fears."
    # [Scene: Salt Flats and Living Breakwater Site | Afternoon]

    scene bg ch15_3be532_3 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Sparse piano, descending; wind like whispered accusation]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: The distant clank of machinery as non-community contractors begin to erect temporary walls]
    "At the flats, contractors in corporate safety vests arrive with neat lines and calibrated shovels. Their emergency fortifications are bright and convincing from a distance — modular panels bolted together, signs touting 'Immediate Protection' and 'Funded"
    "by Private Partnership.' They play on urgency: do something now or watch everything be swept away."
    "Some of the town answers that call. An elderly family agrees to have their front wall raised because the contractor promises immediate repairs; a fisher signs a short-term contract for wage labor that keeps a roof"
    "over a child's head but costs access to seasonal beds. You feel each compromise like a small loss of land."
    "Jonah stands on a ridge of piled earth, his hands folded in front of him as if measuring the tide by the angle of his palms. He watches the contractors with an expression that could be"
    "either fierce contempt or weary acceptance. He does not wave you over; he allows you to find him."
    show jonah_merrick at left:
        zoom 0.7

    jonah_merrick "You did what you had to, child. You kept your name clean. But clean names don't stop a rising house when the contractor takes the time-lag and calls it care."
    "You move closer, smelling cigar smoke and brine on him — scent layered like sediment."
    show isla_morgan at right:
        zoom 0.7

    isla_morgan "Jonah, they said temporary. They said jobs. I thought if we bought time, we could re-enter with the real plan once the review comes back."
    "Jonah's eyes track the jagged line where the modular wall meets the mud."

    jonah_merrick "They always have a 'temporary.' That word is a loop. I've seen temporary become permanent and then the sea takes the rest. You did what's right with data. But right is a lonely place when people are cold."
    "His voice holds no anger toward you, only a tired report. You feel the echo of his words inside your ribs: right can be lonely."

    menu:
        "Help Jonah with the nets, keep up appearances":
            "You move to the nets, your fingers stiff from the cold. Helping is an exchange, a small mercy that doesn't alter the course. Jonah's grip surprises you with its steadiness."
        "Press the contractors publicly about their materials":
            "You ask a foreman about the foundation specs. He shrugs, the language coated in corporate assurances. You leave with a pamphlet that reads like hope packaged for sale."

    # --- merge ---
    "The review lingers while contractors pour in; the coalition begins to creak."
    "As the review lingers and contractors pour in, the coalition you had built begins to creak. Folks who were willing to listen to a long, careful plan opt for immediate assurances: wages today instead of promises"
    "next season, shelter this month instead of resilience later. Luca Moreno's flyers, his late-night assemblies on the rooftop garden, can only do so much when machines and signboards promise immediate answers."
    # [Scene: Greyhaven Harbor | Early Evening — storm front forming]
    hide jonah_merrick
    hide isla_morgan

    scene bg ch15_3be532_4 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Drums and low brass; a rising, inevitable cadence]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: A distant barge horn, now closer; the staccato of small objects beaten by sudden wind]
    "You are back at the lab as the peer review continues its slow, deliberate pace. You have given them everything: raw files, annotated models, context. You have made your argument transparent because leaving no seam is how you believed truth would hold."
    "But transparency does not slow storms."
    "When the storm hits, it is a thing that learns the town's weak spots at lightning speed. Wind takes the edge off the seawall where the modular panels meet; where the contractor's temporary foundations were not"
    "keyed into living reef lines, they tilt and scoot. Water finds seams and enters living rooms, doorways, fishery sheds."
    "You run like many do — to help, to anchor, to pull a neighbor's mattress out of the rising water. Luca Moreno is there at first, shouting instructions, using his harness to pull a stranded pump"
    "from a flooded inlet. He is all hands and clatter and grief made movement. For a moment he looks like the person who believes people can change tides with enough will."
    show luca_moreno at left:
        zoom 0.7

    luca_moreno "Move the sandbags here! Tie the pumps! Get everyone to higher ground!"
    show isla_morgan at right:
        zoom 0.7

    isla_morgan "The contractor's barricade—it's failing where it's not tied into the flats! We need to..."
    "A crane's cable snaps with a horrendous metallic scream. Contractors shout into radios; some retreat into trucks. The developer's PR team organizes volunteers into a line to clear debris; engineers with clipboards confer in tight, awful"
    "circles. Where you need coordination between the community's living defenses and the newly installed structures, bureaucracy gums the gears."
    "You throw your weight where you can, hauling and hauling until your arms go numb, until the ring on your finger leaves a print on your skin that feels like a map."
    "Jonah collapses onto a bench near the harbor, coughing hard, his face drawn and white beneath the brim of his hat. The sea, which took his brother long ago, seems to have reached back with a note of scorn."
    "Someone helps Jonah to his feet but his breath jerks like a net that's been pulled tight too quickly."
    show jonah_merrick at center:
        zoom 0.7

    jonah_merrick "Five years ain't come and gone easy, Isla. Don't make me a story you'll regret."
    "You grip his shoulder. His skin is papery and warm with exertion. You want to keep him standing. You want to stop the angularity of loss from sharpening."
    "Luca Moreno works until something breaks between you."
    "After the worst of the first surge, when the town begins the math on water and hours, the developer's crews consolidate hold and the contractors focus on defending the asset lines they've been contracted to protect."
    "Funding is diverted to 'priority' walls that preserve the new installation's integrity — not always the elders' homes, not always the fishers' drying sheds."
    "Luca Moreno returns to the lab late that night, caked in mud, his jaw set. He sits across from you at the bench, and the lab's small lamp carves a pool of light that feels too intimate for what comes next."

    luca_moreno "They promised they'd coordinate with us. They didn't. They locked their plans and the men to them. While we argued ethics, they moved in protections that left the others exposed."

    isla_morgan "We asked for verification. We asked for certainty. If I had signed—"
    "His laugh is brittle."

    luca_moreno "If you had signed, we'd have had a quick funding pipe and maybe different priorities. But the quick money doesn't mean the right priorities, Isla. Sometimes the quick is exactly what makes things worse."

    isla_morgan "I don't know what would have been better. I don't know how to weigh a life against a model."
    "Luca Moreno's hand slams the table; it might have been an accident, but it's also a punctuation."

    luca_moreno "You think I'm saying you were wrong. I'm saying I'm tired of arguing with the tide while people drown. We need to act, not clean up after..."
    "His voice breaks. For a breath you see the man who saved a child's dog by diving into a flooded alley last winter; for another, you see the organizer who promised half his life to Greyhaven and now holds an empty half."
    "He stands up abruptly."

    luca_moreno "I have to go. There are other places calling where teams are doing what we couldn't get done here. They need me. Maybe I'll come back when the town rebuilds in a different shape."

    isla_morgan "Luca—"
    "He moves without looking back, palms full of mud and grief. The door shuts behind him with the finality of a boat pulling away."
    "You are left with coils of silence and the ledger on the bench like a patient, terrible thing."
    # [Scene: Tidewatch Lab | Night — after the storm]
    hide luca_moreno
    hide isla_morgan
    hide jonah_merrick

    scene bg ch15_3be532_5 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Sparse, elegiac strings; a single clarinet line like a questioning breath]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: The town's low, uncomfortable hum of generators; distant yelling, then quieter sobs]
    "Jonah's health declines over the next days. Pneumonia, the doctor says in blunt municipal language. The fishers' nets are shredded beyond repair. The flats are scarred where heavy machinery carved temporary trenches. Some families who accepted"
    "the contractor's quick-fix find themselves with a roof but cut off from their traditional beds. Old patterns are rearranged into new vulnerabilities."
    "You catalog every loss like a scientist cataloging a collapsed sample. Each data point is a face: the fisher who lost three weeks' catch; the rooftop gardeners whose soil washed out; Jonah coughing into a blanket."
    "You mark dates, times, observed failures. You annotate what could have been avoided if coordination had been whole; you note what could not be predicted even with the best models."
    "At night, you slide your palm over the brass compass that sits on the bench. The metal is warm from use. It is of no practical help now; the sea improvises in ways compasses cannot map."
    "But you lay it against your sternum because you need a small object to act as witness."

    scene bg ch15_3be532_6 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Piano low and steady, then a pause]
    "There is a letter of resignation on Aria Chen's desk when the council reconvenes weeks later. Her public statement is precise and quiet: she takes responsibility for certain oversights, pledges to step back while the town"
    "reforms its procurement processes. Her eyes are unreadable when you pass her in the hall; there is no triumph in the way she looks at you, only a complex knot of relief and regret."
    "Some of the procedural changes you help form are worthwhile: clearer contracting guidelines, a community oversight board that includes fishers and gardeners, grants for living breakwater pilot projects. They are scaffolding, imperfect and slow. The worst"
    "wounds in the harbor are visible for years — a blackened line on old boards, a new seam where patched wood meets old. The town learns to measure its losses against the cost of not speaking"
    "up; that lesson is bitter and expensive."
    "Luca Moreno does not return. You learn, months later, that he is working with an emergency-response cooperative two towns down, teaching people to stitch quick pumps into old engines, building modular breakaways in places that have"
    "money and momentum. The news of his small victories arrives in a stray text — a photo of a repaired pump, a smiling face, a speech peppered with the same jokes that once softened your meetings."
    "You read them and close your eyes. There is pride, and a rupture, and a tenderness you are not yet ready to name."
    "Jonah dies in late spring, like a tide that finally leaves the shore. You stand at his small service atop the promenade, the town wrapped in a quiet that smells of salt and rain-soaked wreaths. Maya's"
    "hands are small and fierce when she steadies you. The compass in your pocket feels heavier than ever, and when you take it out to lay it on Jonah's coffin you realize the metal has dulled"
    "in the months since the storm. It is tarnished with salt that will not polish off."
    "You speak at Jonah's service because no one else can find the words that are both true and small enough to fit. You tell a story of an old man who taught you to read currents"
    "by watching a boat's wake. You tell the truth carefully: that he loved the town's ways and taught you to love them enough to defend them. Your voice breaks in the places where memory is an"
    "aperture to grief."
    # [Scene: Tidewatch Lab | Dawn — the aftermath settles to a new normal]

    scene bg ch15_3be532_7 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: A single violin note sustaining, then resolving into silence]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: A gull, then only the distant clank of repair]
    "You sit down at the bench and open the ledger one last time. You read through your own annotations and the peer reviews that finally, slowly, corroborate your concerns. The review vindicates the technical points: certain"
    "hydrodynamic interactions and the developer's assumptions are shown to be flawed. The language is clinical and sharp; it does not heal tongues or fill nets. It only does what evidence does best: assert what was true."
    "In the public meetings that follow, the review is used to rewrite procurement rules and to bind developers to community-led oversight. The reforms are messy. They are not enough for everything that was lost. They are,"
    "however, a map forward that bears your fingerprints and the fingerprints of others who started from a place of careful refusal."
    "You are left with consequences that do not scab. The town learned hard and bitter lessons; some things will never be the same. You carry Jonah's absence, Luca's leaving, the eroded edges of Greyhaven like a wound that will not close."
    "And in the quiet that follows the legal scrawl and the committee meetings, in the lab where the lamp burns sometimes into the night, you find a small steadier thing: an understanding that truth is not always soft, but its hardness can be used to build."
    show isla_morgan at left:
        zoom 0.7

    isla_morgan "I wanted to save everything. I could not. I can still try to prevent this happening again."
    "You put the compass back into your apron, fingers finding the dent where your father's thumb had once rested. You press your palm flat and feel the cold, and then the faint, impossible warmth that comes when you set one small thing down and stand up again."
    hide isla_morgan

    scene bg ch15_3be532_8 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Final chord — minor, resolved]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Ocean, steadier now; a clock striking the hour]
    "You will carry the ledger's truth and its cost. You will labor with it in council rooms and on muddy flats. You will test new living breakwaters in the places you can persuade people to trust you. You will be grief and stubbornness and science braided together."
    "It is not the ending you wanted. It is not a defeat that erases purpose. It is a life rearranged around the knowledge that some sacrifices are immediate and some are deferred. The town endures in"
    "a different shape, and you endure with it — not whole, not the same, but moving forward with the hard kind of care that looks a lot like love."

    scene bg ch15_3be532_9 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Fade to a single, low piano note; then silence]

    scene bg ch15_3be532_10 at full_bg
    "THE END"
    # [GAME END]
    return
